1
00:00:24,482 --> 00:00:26,746
I'm talkin'about friendship.

2
00:00:26,818 --> 00:00:29,481
I'm talkin'about character.

3
00:00:29,555 --> 00:00:33,993
I'm talkin'about-- Hell, Leo,
I ain't embarrassed to use the word.

4
00:00:34,061 --> 00:00:37,224
I'm talkin' about ethics.

5
00:00:37,297 --> 00:00:39,357
You know I'm a sportin' man.

6
00:00:39,434 --> 00:00:41,868
I like to lay the occasional bet.

7
00:00:41,936 --> 00:00:44,497
But I ain't that sportin'.

8
00:00:44,573 --> 00:00:47,474
When I fix a fight--
Say I pay a three to one favorite...

9
00:00:47,543 --> 00:00:49,569
to throw a goddamned fight.

10
00:00:49,646 --> 00:00:53,777
I figure I got the right to expect that fight
to go off at three to one.

11
00:00:53,851 --> 00:00:57,582
But every time I lay in bed
with this son of a bitch Bernie Bernbaum,

12
00:00:57,655 --> 00:01:00,955
before I know it, the odds is even up.

13
00:01:01,026 --> 00:01:03,587
Or worse, I'm bettin' on the short money.

14
00:01:03,663 --> 00:01:05,927
The sheeny knows I like sure things.

15
00:01:05,999 --> 00:01:09,458
He's sellin' the information I fixed the fight.

16
00:01:09,536 --> 00:01:11,902
Out of town money comes pouring in.

17
00:01:11,972 --> 00:01:14,203
The odds go straight to hell.

18
00:01:14,276 --> 00:01:17,643
I don't know who he's sellin' to--
maybe the Los Angeles combine.

19
00:01:17,712 --> 00:01:19,647
I don't know. The point is,

20
00:01:19,715 --> 00:01:23,879
Bernie ain't satisfied with the honest dollar
he can make off the vig.

21
00:01:23,953 --> 00:01:27,185
He ain't satisfied
with the business I do on his book.

22
00:01:27,257 --> 00:01:30,159
He is sellin' tips on how I bet.

23
00:01:30,228 --> 00:01:33,391
And that means part of the payoff
 that should be riding on my hip...

24
00:01:33,464 --> 00:01:35,626
is riding on someone else's.

25
00:01:35,701 --> 00:01:38,226
So, back we go to these questions--

26
00:01:38,304 --> 00:01:42,173
friendship, character,

27
00:01:42,242 --> 00:01:44,574
ethics.

28
00:01:47,715 --> 00:01:49,774
So, it's clear what I'm saying?

29
00:01:51,219 --> 00:01:54,086
As mud.

30
00:01:56,659 --> 00:02:02,394
It's gettin' so a businessman
can't expect no return from a fixed fight.

31
00:02:02,466 --> 00:02:05,925
Now, if you can't trust a fix, what can you trust?

32
00:02:06,004 --> 00:02:09,405
For a good return,you gotta go bettin'on chance,

33
00:02:09,474 --> 00:02:11,705
and then you're back with anarchy.

34
00:02:11,777 --> 00:02:13,711
Right back in the jungle.

35
00:02:13,779 --> 00:02:18,843
That's why ethics is important--
what separates us from the animals,

36
00:02:18,919 --> 00:02:21,388
the beasts of burden, the beasts of prey.

37
00:02:21,456 --> 00:02:23,424
Ethics.

38
00:02:23,491 --> 00:02:27,690
Whereas, uh, Bernie Bernbaum
is a horse of a different color,

39
00:02:27,763 --> 00:02:31,494
ethics-wise, as in he ain't got any.

40
00:02:31,568 --> 00:02:35,664
- You sure it's Bernie selling you out?
- It ain't elves.

41
00:02:35,739 --> 00:02:39,608
- No one else knows about the fix?
 - No one that ain't got ethics.

42
00:02:39,677 --> 00:02:42,704
What about the fighters you pay to tank out?

43
00:02:42,781 --> 00:02:46,717
We only pick fighters we know
 we can put the fear of God in.

44
00:02:46,785 --> 00:02:49,084
Any other bookies know?
You play anyone else's book?

45
00:02:49,155 --> 00:02:52,387
I-I lay an occasional bet with Mink Larouie.

46
00:02:52,459 --> 00:02:54,984
- But it ain't Mink. I'll vouch for that.
 -How do you know?

47
00:02:55,062 --> 00:02:58,328
It ain't Mink. Mink is Eddie Dane's boy.

48
00:02:58,400 --> 00:03:02,234
Of course the Dane always knows about the fix.

49
00:03:02,303 --> 00:03:04,431
And what the hell is that supposed to mean?

50
00:03:04,507 --> 00:03:08,035
Let it drift.
 All it means is a lot of people know.

51
00:03:08,111 --> 00:03:10,477
I guess you ain't been listenin'.

52
00:03:10,547 --> 00:03:12,742
Sure, other people know.

53
00:03:12,816 --> 00:03:15,513
That's why we gotta go
 to this question of character...

54
00:03:15,586 --> 00:03:19,284
to determine just who, exactly,
 is chiselin' in on my fix.

55
00:03:19,358 --> 00:03:23,124
And that's how we know
that it's Bernie Bernbaum, the shmatte kid--

56
00:03:23,195 --> 00:03:26,290
'cause ethically, he's kinda shaky.

57
00:03:27,534 --> 00:03:31,596
- So you want to kill him.
- For starters.

58
00:03:46,023 --> 00:03:50,552
Sorry, Caspar. Bernie pays for protection.

59
00:03:52,063 --> 00:03:55,261
Listen, Leo,
I ain't askin' you for permission.

60
00:03:55,334 --> 00:03:59,498
I'm tellin' you as a courtesy. I need
to do this thing, so it's gonna get done.

61
00:03:59,572 --> 00:04:01,507
And I'm tellin' you, as a courtesy,
you'll have trouble.

62
00:04:01,575 --> 00:04:05,444
You came here to see if I'd kick if you
killed Bernie. Well, there's your answer.

63
00:04:05,513 --> 00:04:09,176
I pay off to you every month
 like a greengrocer

64
00:04:09,250 --> 00:04:11,242
a lot more than the shmatte,

65
00:04:11,320 --> 00:04:13,254
and I'm sick of gettin' the high hat.

66
00:04:13,322 --> 00:04:16,349
You pay off for protection
just like everyone else.

67
00:04:16,426 --> 00:04:19,224
As far as I know, and what I don't know
 in this town ain't worth knowing,

68
00:04:19,295 --> 00:04:21,287
the cops haven't closed any of your dives...

69
00:04:21,365 --> 00:04:23,856
and the D.A. hasn't touched any of your rackets.

70
00:04:23,934 --> 00:04:26,460
You haven't bought any license to kill bookies,

71
00:04:26,538 --> 00:04:28,529
and today I ain't sellin'any.

72
00:04:28,607 --> 00:04:31,509
So take your flunky and dangle.

73
00:04:31,577 --> 00:04:35,981
You think I'm some guinea fresh off the boat,
 and you can kick me.

74
00:04:36,049 --> 00:04:40,110
But I'm too big for that now.
I'm sick of takin' the strap from you, Leo.

75
00:04:40,187 --> 00:04:42,554
I'm sick of marching into this goddamn office...

76
00:04:42,624 --> 00:04:44,649
to kiss your Irish ass,

77
00:05:03,849 --> 00:05:07,149
You's fancy pants, all of youse.

78
00:05:09,022 --> 00:05:11,490
Johnny?

79
00:05:11,558 --> 00:05:14,892
You're exactly as big
 as I let you be and no bigger,

80
00:05:14,962 --> 00:05:17,260
and don't forget it, ever.

81
00:05:19,834 --> 00:05:21,768
That's right, Leo.

82
00:05:21,836 --> 00:05:23,930
You're the big shot around here,

83
00:05:24,006 --> 00:05:27,669
and I'm just some schnook
likes to get slapped around.

84
00:05:35,053 --> 00:05:38,022
Twist a pig's ear, watch him squeal.

85
00:05:46,700 --> 00:05:50,262
- Bad play, Leo.
- Who got up the wrong side, huh?

86
00:05:50,338 --> 00:05:53,171
-Same side as always.
- That's what I mean. Still owe money to--

87
00:05:53,240 --> 00:05:56,699
Who is your bookie, Lazarre?
I could put it right for you.

88
00:05:56,778 --> 00:05:59,805
- Thanks, Leo. I don't need it.
- In a pig's eye.

89
00:05:59,882 --> 00:06:01,816
You haven't played a winner in six weeks.

90
00:06:01,884 --> 00:06:04,285
People will speak ill of me
if I let him break your legs.

91
00:06:04,355 --> 00:06:08,223
- People will say I had it coming.
-And they'll be right, but that ain't the point.

92
00:06:08,292 --> 00:06:12,161
Call me a bighearted slob,
but I'm gonna square it for you, yeah.

93
00:06:12,230 --> 00:06:15,689
I think I'll do that this very same night.

94
00:06:15,768 --> 00:06:19,636
Lookin' at you mopin' around
takes away all my--

95
00:06:19,706 --> 00:06:23,420
- What do you call it? ''Joy de veever''?
-Joie de vivre.

96
00:06:23,513 --> 00:06:25,471
 Well, if you're gonna laugh at me,
 the hell with ya.

97
00:06:25,546 --> 00:06:28,174
The hell with you.

98
00:06:28,249 --> 00:06:30,650
I'll square myself with Lazarre,
 if you don't mind.

99
00:06:30,719 --> 00:06:33,620
That's why God invented cards.

100
00:06:36,126 --> 00:06:38,959
- There is one thing you can do for me.
- Name it.

101
00:06:39,029 --> 00:06:41,521
Think about what protecting Bernie gets us.

102
00:06:41,599 --> 00:06:44,193
Think about what offending Caspar loses us.

103
00:06:44,268 --> 00:06:46,635
Oh, come on, Tommy.
You know I don't like to think.

104
00:06:46,705 --> 00:06:48,764
Yeah.

105
00:06:48,840 --> 00:06:52,812
Well, think about whether you should start.

106
00:08:37,202 --> 00:08:39,534
Wake up, Tommy.

107
00:08:39,605 --> 00:08:42,734
- I am awake.
- Your eyes are shut.

108
00:08:42,809 --> 00:08:45,074
Who you gonna believe?

109
00:08:55,625 --> 00:08:58,253
- How'd I do?
- What do you think?

110
00:08:58,328 --> 00:09:01,162
You are a millionaire.
You gonna remember your friends?

111
00:09:04,501 --> 00:09:08,165
- Where's me hat?
- You bet it, mug.

112
00:09:08,239 --> 00:09:11,767
Good thing the game broke up
before you bet your trousers.

113
00:09:12,979 --> 00:09:16,245
- Who made off with me hat?

114
00:09:16,316 --> 00:09:19,114
Verna. Verna and Mink.

115
00:09:19,186 --> 00:09:21,587
- Who?
- Mink and Verna.

116
00:09:29,331 --> 00:09:31,698
Is Thunderclap running tonight?

117
00:09:31,768 --> 00:09:34,999
Thunderclap?
Yeah.

118
00:09:35,071 --> 00:09:37,097
What's she leaving at?

119
00:09:37,174 --> 00:09:39,836
Three to one, more than likely.

120
00:09:39,910 --> 00:09:43,142
Lay off, Tom.
You shouldn't go deeper in the hole.

121
00:09:43,215 --> 00:09:45,740
Tell Lazarre...

122
00:09:45,817 --> 00:09:49,276
I want 500 on the nose.

123
00:09:49,355 --> 00:09:51,915
You would have it.

124
00:10:04,807 --> 00:10:07,503
I want me hat.

125
00:10:07,576 --> 00:10:11,377
Is that all you came for?

126
00:10:11,448 --> 00:10:13,781
Yeah. I want me hat.

127
00:10:13,851 --> 00:10:16,012
It's mine. I won it.

128
00:10:16,087 --> 00:10:18,852
- What are you gonna do with it?
- Drop dead.

129
00:10:27,300 --> 00:10:30,202
I need a drink.

130
00:10:30,271 --> 00:10:32,899
Why didn't you say so?

131
00:11:29,374 --> 00:11:32,469
Hello, Tommy.
Sorry about the hour.

132
00:11:32,545 --> 00:11:36,380
- I'll live. What's the rumpus?
-Can I come in?

133
00:11:38,952 --> 00:11:41,478
Sure.

134
00:11:50,132 --> 00:11:53,330
- Drink?
- I wouldn't mind.

135
00:12:00,144 --> 00:12:02,306
I tried callin' earlier.

136
00:12:02,381 --> 00:12:05,009
I got home late.

137
00:12:10,223 --> 00:12:15,594
- Well, uh, I'm sorry about the hour.
- Uh-huh.

138
00:12:27,945 --> 00:12:31,540
- Not bad.
- Better than the paint we sell at the club.

139
00:12:31,615 --> 00:12:34,244
That it is. That it is.

140
00:12:37,789 --> 00:12:40,020
- You thought about cutting Bernie loose?
 - Can't do it, Tommy.

141
00:12:40,092 --> 00:12:43,084
Can't do it.

142
00:12:43,162 --> 00:12:45,688
That's sort of why I'm, uh--

143
00:12:48,301 --> 00:12:51,328
Tommy, I don't know where Verna is.

144
00:12:51,405 --> 00:12:54,705
- Uh-huh.
 - I know what you're thinkin', what else is new?

145
00:12:54,776 --> 00:12:57,768
But the situation now--
I'm worried.

146
00:12:57,846 --> 00:13:01,283
Verna can take care of herself,
 maybe better than you can.

147
00:13:01,351 --> 00:13:04,947
- What does that mean?
- Want another one?

148
00:13:05,022 --> 00:13:06,956
No.

149
00:13:07,024 --> 00:13:09,083
What does that mean?

150
00:13:09,159 --> 00:13:11,560
How far she got
her hooks into you?

151
00:13:11,630 --> 00:13:13,723
That's a hell of a question.

152
00:13:15,868 --> 00:13:18,132
It's a grift.

153
00:13:18,204 --> 00:13:21,868
If she didn't need you to protect
her brother from Johnny Caspar,

154
00:13:21,942 --> 00:13:25,606
you think she'd still be going on slow
 carriage rides with you through the park?

155
00:13:25,680 --> 00:13:30,084
That's the deal, isn't it? You keep Bernie
 under wraps till Caspar cools down?

156
00:13:30,152 --> 00:13:34,020
Jesus, you're a prickly pear. What's wrong
with her wanting her brother taken care of?

157
00:13:34,089 --> 00:13:36,024
Nothing. I don't blame her.

158
00:13:36,092 --> 00:13:38,424
She sees the angle,
which is you, she plays it.

159
00:13:38,495 --> 00:13:41,465
She's a grifter, just like her brother.

160
00:13:41,532 --> 00:13:43,796
Probably had grifter parents
and grifter grandparents...

161
00:13:43,868 --> 00:13:46,963
and someday they're each
 gonna spawn little grifter kids.

162
00:13:47,039 --> 00:13:50,270
Stop it, Tommy. I don't like to hear
 my friends run down, even by other friends.

163
00:13:50,342 --> 00:13:52,538
- Friendship's got nothing to do with it.
- The hell you say.

164
00:13:52,612 --> 00:13:55,376
You'd do anything to help your friends,
 like you'd do anything to kick your enemies.

165
00:13:55,448 --> 00:13:57,019
- Wrong, Leo. You do things for a reason.
- Okay, Tom.

166
00:13:57,019 --> 00:13:58,953
- Wrong, Leo. You do things for a reason.
- Okay, Tom.

167
00:13:59,021 --> 00:14:02,219
You know all the angles,
Christ, better than anybody.

168
00:14:04,193 --> 00:14:07,391
But maybe you're wrong about this.
You don't know what's in Verna's heart.

169
00:14:07,464 --> 00:14:10,331
Leo, if she's such an angel,

170
00:14:10,401 --> 00:14:12,666
why are you looking for her
at 4:00 in the morning?

171
00:14:17,076 --> 00:14:19,010
I put a tail on her this afternoon.

172
00:14:20,446 --> 00:14:25,077
- Uh-huh.
- I asked Rug Daniels to follow her around,

173
00:14:25,152 --> 00:14:28,350
just, you know, to keep her out of trouble.

174
00:14:28,423 --> 00:14:32,554
I was worried. After that meeting
with Caspar, you can't be too careful.

175
00:14:32,628 --> 00:14:35,057
So what did Rug say
that has you scurrying over here?

176
00:14:35,332 --> 00:14:41,665
 That's just it. Nothing.
He's disappeared.

177
00:14:39,012 --> 00:14:42,112
So you lost your lady friend
and the tail you put on her?

178
00:14:42,195 --> 00:14:44,333
I guess it does sound pretty sorry at that.

179
00:14:44,408 --> 00:14:47,867
Help me out, Tom.
I wouldn't know where to start lookin'.

180
00:14:47,946 --> 00:14:50,506
You know Rug's crowd.
 You know the people Verna runs with.

181
00:14:50,582 --> 00:14:54,212
It's just I'm worried now with things
the way they are between me and Caspar.

182
00:14:54,287 --> 00:14:57,120
You shouldn't be confronting Johnny Caspar.
 That's what I've been trying to tell you.

183
00:14:57,190 --> 00:15:00,024
You can't trade body blows with him.
He's gotten too strong.

184
00:15:00,094 --> 00:15:04,122
I reckon I can still trade body blows
 with any man in this town.

185
00:15:08,236 --> 00:15:10,967
Except you, Tom.

186
00:15:11,040 --> 00:15:12,974
And Verna.

187
00:15:22,954 --> 00:15:25,549
Okay. Give me the needle.

188
00:15:27,426 --> 00:15:30,555
I am a sap.

189
00:15:30,630 --> 00:15:33,963
I deserve it.

190
00:15:34,033 --> 00:15:36,127
Thanks for the drink.

191
00:15:37,571 --> 00:15:39,938
Let me know if you hear anything.

192
00:16:08,508 --> 00:16:12,070
- Who was that?
- Leo.

193
00:16:12,146 --> 00:16:14,376
He's lookin' for you.

194
00:16:14,448 --> 00:16:16,917
Did you tell him I was here?

195
00:16:16,985 --> 00:16:19,476
No.

196
00:16:21,925 --> 00:16:25,326
Did you put in a good word for my brother?

197
00:16:25,395 --> 00:16:27,489
No.

198
00:16:27,565 --> 00:16:30,796
- You said you would.
- I said I'd think about it.

199
00:16:32,904 --> 00:16:35,065
What did you tell him?

200
00:16:38,110 --> 00:16:40,943
Did you see Rug Daniels last night?

201
00:16:41,013 --> 00:16:43,380
No.

202
00:16:43,450 --> 00:16:45,543
What did you tell Leo?

203
00:16:45,619 --> 00:16:48,282
I told him you were a tramp
and he should dump you.

204
00:16:52,227 --> 00:16:55,061
You're a son of a bitch, Tom.

205
00:18:08,251 --> 00:18:10,379
- Hello, Tom. What's the rumpus?
- Mink.

206
00:18:10,454 --> 00:18:12,547
- I see you got your hat back.
- Yeah, what of it?

207
00:18:12,623 --> 00:18:14,716
Not a thing. Look, if it ain't my business,
I got not a thing to say.

208
00:18:14,792 --> 00:18:16,727
Listen, Bernie wants to see you.
It's important.

209
00:18:16,795 --> 00:18:18,729
Yeah, well, I'm right here.
I'm not made of glass.

210
00:18:18,797 --> 00:18:21,460
He's nervous walkin' around in public.
He's a right guy, but he's very nervous.

211
00:18:21,534 --> 00:18:24,128
I mean, who wouldn't be?
In the spot he's in, who wouldn't be?

212
00:18:24,203 --> 00:18:26,536
He asked me to ask you
to ask Leo to take care of him.

213
00:18:26,606 --> 00:18:28,631
Leo listens to you. Not that Leo
wouldn't help a shmatte anyway.

214
00:18:28,709 --> 00:18:31,042
A guy like Bernie?
A straight shooter like him?

215
00:18:31,112 --> 00:18:32,014
- I don't get it, Mink.

216
00:18:32,344 --> 00:18:33,847
- What's to get?
It's as plain as the nose on your face.

217
00:18:33,947 --> 00:18:36,314
- I tell you were Eddie Dane's sycophant.
- Yeah, Tom, that's right,

218
00:18:36,385 --> 00:18:37,820
but a guy can have more
than one friend, can't he?

219
00:18:37,920 --> 00:18:41,109
Not that I want the Dane to know about it,
but the shmatte, he's a right guy, Tommy.

220
00:18:41,591 --> 00:18:44,189
He's got a mixed reputation, but for a sheeny,
  he's got a lot of good qualities.

221
00:18:44,260 --> 00:18:47,526
- What's goin' on between you and Bernie?
- Nothin', Tom.

222
00:18:47,598 --> 00:18:49,623
We're just...
friends, you know, amigos.

223
00:18:50,550 --> 00:18:51,675
You're a fickle boy, Mink.

224
00:18:52,137 --> 00:18:56,437
If Eddie Dane finds out
that you got another ''amigo''--

225
00:18:56,508 --> 00:18:58,735
- Well, I don't peg him
for the understanding type.

226
00:18:59,147 --> 00:19:01,598
 Find out? How's he gonna find out?
Damn, Tommy!

227
00:19:01,698 --> 00:19:04,739
You and me haven't even been talking!
Jesus, Tommy! Goddamn it, Jesus!

228
00:19:07,722 --> 00:19:10,247
Hello, Tommy.

229
00:19:10,325 --> 00:19:13,523
- You know O'Doole and the mayor?
-I oughta.

230
00:19:13,596 --> 00:19:16,258
Voted for him six times last May.

231
00:19:16,332 --> 00:19:18,392
And that ain't the record, either.

232
00:19:20,470 --> 00:19:24,601
Oh, Verna turned up. She's downstairs.

233
00:19:24,675 --> 00:19:28,009
- She say where she'd been?
 - No. I didn't want to press her.

234
00:19:28,080 --> 00:19:32,449
- You hear about Rug?
- Yeah. R.I.P.

235
00:19:32,518 --> 00:19:35,511
They took his hair, Tommy.

236
00:19:35,588 --> 00:19:38,285
Jesus, that's strange.
Why would they do that?

237
00:19:38,359 --> 00:19:42,853
- Maybe it was injuns.
- ''Eye-ties,'' more like it.

238
00:19:45,033 --> 00:19:46,967
Giovanni Gasparo.

239
00:19:47,035 --> 00:19:49,903
So you figure Caspar bumped Rug.

240
00:19:49,972 --> 00:19:52,600
- Well, it's pretty obvious, ain't it?
- Yeah?

241
00:19:52,675 --> 00:19:54,342
- So what's the plan?

242
00:19:55,013 --> 00:19:57,400
 - Well, we'll jump on the guinea hard
 with both feet.

243
00:19:57,748 --> 00:20:01,241
- Give him the lowdown, Dale.
- Yes. Well, um,

244
00:20:01,319 --> 00:20:04,049
Leo here just reminded us
 that Mr. Caspar operates...

245
00:20:04,123 --> 00:20:06,148
several clubs in our city,

246
00:20:06,225 --> 00:20:10,219
wherein the patrons imbibe of rum
and play at games of chance.

247
00:20:10,297 --> 00:20:12,458
And we're supposed to stop the party.

248
00:20:12,532 --> 00:20:15,593
- They don't look to happy about it, Leo.
 - Oh, no, it ain't that, Tom.

249
00:20:15,670 --> 00:20:18,730
-Jesus, Tom, we do as we're told.
- Maybe they're right not to like it.

250
00:20:18,806 --> 00:20:21,935
Stirring up this hornet's nest won't be good
for anyone, and it'll mean killing.

251
00:20:22,010 --> 00:20:25,105
I'm not thrilled about it either,
 but I can't just lay down to Caspar.

252
00:20:25,181 --> 00:20:27,741
You could do worse. You might not like it,
but giving up Bernie Bernbaum...

253
00:20:27,817 --> 00:20:29,785
is a pretty small price to pay for peace.

254
00:20:29,853 --> 00:20:32,948
Business is business,
and a war is going to hurt everybody.

255
00:20:33,023 --> 00:20:35,356
Bernie plays with fire, he's got
 to deal with the consequences.

256
00:20:35,427 --> 00:20:37,418
even if that means he gets bumped off.

257
00:20:37,496 --> 00:20:41,490
SweetJesus, Tom, that ain't even
the point anymore. Caspar pooped Rug.

258
00:20:41,567 --> 00:20:44,400
The day I back down from a fight,
Caspar's welcome to the rackets,

259
00:20:44,470 --> 00:20:46,530
this town and my place at the table.

260
00:20:46,607 --> 00:20:48,700
- I didn't start this thing, but--
- You did start it.

261
00:20:48,775 --> 00:20:52,268
- You and Verna.
- We can dangle, Leo, if you'd prefer.

262
00:20:54,449 --> 00:20:57,908
And Caspar hasn't broken the rules,
 Bernie has, and you, too, by helping him.

263
00:20:57,987 --> 00:21:00,148
And if that isn't enough,
 consider that if you make this a war,

264
00:21:00,222 --> 00:21:02,384
you have more to lose than Caspar.

265
00:21:02,459 --> 00:21:06,556
Okay, but more to beat him with. Jesus, Tom,
the two of us have faced worse odds.

266
00:21:06,631 --> 00:21:10,168
Never without reason.
It helps to have one.

267
00:21:15,641 --> 00:21:18,577
Well, it's your call.

268
00:21:20,213 --> 00:21:22,512
My opinion used to count for something
around here.

269
00:21:22,583 --> 00:21:24,710
But it's always yours to take or leave.

270
00:21:24,785 --> 00:21:26,719
Come on, Tommy. It's not like that.

271
00:21:33,563 --> 00:21:36,327
Goddamn kid's just like a twist.

272
00:21:36,399 --> 00:21:38,891
Get me a stiff one.

273
00:21:40,304 --> 00:21:42,602
No small talk, huh?

274
00:21:44,842 --> 00:21:48,108
- They shoot your horse?
- If there's any justice.

275
00:21:49,548 --> 00:21:52,039
- Verna around?
 - She stepped into the ladies' room.

276
00:21:52,117 --> 00:21:55,383
- You got Lazarre's 500?
- You'll have to carry me for a few days.

277
00:21:55,455 --> 00:21:58,516
He ain't gonna like that.
Couldn't you get it from Leo?

278
00:21:58,593 --> 00:22:01,892
It's not Leo's debt.
I'll pay me own way.

279
00:22:01,963 --> 00:22:03,864
I admire a man of principle.

280
00:22:05,634 --> 00:22:08,604
Does this go on the tab?

281
00:22:08,671 --> 00:22:11,367
- Close your eyes, ladies.
I'm coming through.

282
00:22:15,713 --> 00:22:19,241
- Who's the war paint for?
- Go home and dry out.

283
00:22:20,418 --> 00:22:22,443
You don't need it for Leo, believe me.

284
00:22:22,520 --> 00:22:24,989
He already thinks you're
the original Miss Jesus.

285
00:22:25,057 --> 00:22:27,184
- What the hell's the matter with you?
 - What's the matter with you?

286
00:22:27,260 --> 00:22:30,822
- Afraid people might get the right idea?
 - Leo's got the right idea.

287
00:22:30,897 --> 00:22:33,559
I like him.
He's honest and he's got a heart.

288
00:22:33,634 --> 00:22:35,899
Then it's true what they say--
opposites attract.

289
00:22:35,970 --> 00:22:39,462
- Do me a favor. Mind your own business.
- This is my business.

290
00:22:39,540 --> 00:22:42,408
Intimidating helpless women
is part of what I do.

291
00:22:42,478 --> 00:22:44,639
- Then find one and intimidate her.
-Leo's upstairs...

292
00:22:44,713 --> 00:22:47,080
getting ready to shoot himself
in the foot on your account.

293
00:22:47,150 --> 00:22:49,084
-I don't know what you're talkin'about.
- He's gonna go to the mat...

294
00:22:49,152 --> 00:22:51,087
for your brother, and it's gonna hurt him.

295
00:22:51,155 --> 00:22:53,350
I don't know Leo's business,
but he's a big boy.

296
00:22:53,424 --> 00:22:55,450
- He used to be.
- Look, what do you want, Tom?

297
00:22:55,527 --> 00:22:58,360
You want me to pretend
 I don't care what happens to Bernie?

298
00:22:58,430 --> 00:23:01,161
Well, I do. He's my brother.
I don't want to see him get hurt.

299
00:23:01,234 --> 00:23:05,672
If Leo wants to help out, I'll step out
with him, show him a good time in return.

300
00:23:05,739 --> 00:23:06,968
- There's no harm in that.

301
00:23:07,068 --> 00:23:09,308
 - There's a name
 for that kind of business arrangement.

302
00:23:09,443 --> 00:23:12,704
Look, I'll do what I have to do to protect Bernie.

303
00:23:12,781 --> 00:23:15,113
There's no reason for you to try and queer that.

304
00:23:15,183 --> 00:23:17,812
Regardless of what you think about me,
Bernie's a decent guy.

305
00:23:17,887 --> 00:23:21,551
- A straight shooter, huh? A square ''G.''
- Yeah.

306
00:23:21,625 --> 00:23:25,891
Sneer at him like everyone else,
just because he's different.

307
00:23:25,962 --> 00:23:28,625
People think he's a degenerate.
People think he's scum.

308
00:23:28,700 --> 00:23:32,296
- Well, he's not.
-Poor misunderstood Bernie.

309
00:23:32,371 --> 00:23:34,805
What is this about, Tom?

310
00:23:34,873 --> 00:23:38,310
You want me to stop seeing Leo?
Why don't you just say so?

311
00:23:40,146 --> 00:23:43,583
I want you to quit spinning Leo in circles
 and pointing him where to go.

312
00:23:43,651 --> 00:23:46,119
- I forgot. That's your job.
 - I'll do what I have to do to protect Leo.

313
00:23:46,187 --> 00:23:49,589
I'm asking you politely. Leave him alone.
I don't have to ask.

314
00:23:49,658 --> 00:23:52,856
If I told him about our little dance last night,
your pool would pretty soon dry up.

315
00:23:52,929 --> 00:23:54,988
So would yours.
I don't like being threatened.

316
00:23:55,064 --> 00:23:59,263
I don't like being taken for a sucker. That
might work with Leo, but it don't work with me.

317
00:23:59,336 --> 00:24:02,533
Do you think last night was just
 more campaigning for my brother?

318
00:24:02,606 --> 00:24:04,507
I can see the angles.

319
00:24:04,576 --> 00:24:06,669
You know, if there was a market
 for little old ladies,

320
00:24:06,745 --> 00:24:08,737
you'd have Grandma Bernbaum first in line.

321
00:24:08,814 --> 00:24:11,544
- You're a pathetic rumhead.
- And I love you, angel.

322
00:24:28,036 --> 00:24:31,063
I suppose you think you raised hell.

323
00:24:35,112 --> 00:24:38,707
Sister, when I've raised hell, you'll know it.

324
00:25:18,997 --> 00:25:21,489
- I need a couple of days.
- Yeah? How come is that?

325
00:25:21,568 --> 00:25:25,801
- Because I don't have it.
 - All right, how do I know you ain't got it?

326
00:25:25,873 --> 00:25:29,934
- Because I say so.
- That ain't gonna be good enough.

327
00:25:30,010 --> 00:25:33,606
- What would be good enough?
- Lazarre ain't gonna like it one bit.

328
00:25:33,682 --> 00:25:36,618
Tell Lazarre if he's not happy, he can send
someone over to break my legs.

329
00:25:36,686 --> 00:25:39,678
I won't squawk.

330
00:25:41,325 --> 00:25:44,021
- Hello, Bernie.
- Hello, Tom.

331
00:25:44,094 --> 00:25:47,724
- What's the rumpus?
-Come on in. Make yourself at home.

332
00:25:47,799 --> 00:25:50,359
Yeah, you weren't here,
so I thought I'd do that.

333
00:25:50,435 --> 00:25:52,734
I didn't want to answer the phone,
 though. I figured...

334
00:25:52,805 --> 00:25:54,739
it wasn't for me.

335
00:25:56,542 --> 00:25:59,341
I get it. Get to the point, huh?

336
00:25:59,412 --> 00:26:02,246
Okay. The point is, I'm a good guy.

337
00:26:02,316 --> 00:26:04,250
I've heard that from a lot of people today.

338
00:26:04,318 --> 00:26:06,218
Good guy, lots of friends.
That's the way it works.

339
00:26:06,287 --> 00:26:10,952
Maybe if you appreciated me a little more,
 you wouldn't be making waves with Leo.

340
00:26:11,026 --> 00:26:13,825
It's a bad time to be doing that.
Right now, we're both in a jam.

341
00:26:13,897 --> 00:26:17,561
I hear you're on a bad streak.
Short of funds.

342
00:26:17,635 --> 00:26:20,934
Well, I got that crazy dago mad at me.

343
00:26:21,005 --> 00:26:22,974
Don't ask me why. I'm just a small-timer...

344
00:26:23,041 --> 00:26:25,339
trying to get by like everyone else.

345
00:26:25,410 --> 00:26:28,403
I need help from my friends like Leo and you.

346
00:26:28,481 --> 00:26:30,574
Leo gets your sister.
What are you sellin' me?

347
00:26:30,650 --> 00:26:33,051
Come on, Tom. It's not like that at all.
It wasn't my idea.

348
00:26:33,120 --> 00:26:35,213
She'll sleep with anyone.
You know that.

349
00:26:35,289 --> 00:26:38,953
She even tried to teach me
a thing or two about bed artistry.

350
00:26:39,027 --> 00:26:41,860
Can you believe that?

351
00:26:41,930 --> 00:26:44,195
My own sister.

352
00:26:44,266 --> 00:26:49,398
Some crackpot idea
 about saving me from my friends.

353
00:26:49,472 --> 00:26:51,633
She's a sick twist, all right.

354
00:26:51,708 --> 00:26:55,509
- She speaks highly of you.
- Yeah, well, you stick by your family.

355
00:26:55,580 --> 00:26:58,140
The point is, I can help you with your debts
if that would make us friends.

356
00:26:58,215 --> 00:27:01,617
My motto is, ''A guy can't have too many.''

357
00:27:01,687 --> 00:27:04,919
Big payday Saturday, Tom.
You could be in on it.

358
00:27:04,991 --> 00:27:07,289
Another fix? Which fight?

359
00:27:07,360 --> 00:27:11,422
That's confidential at the moment.
But it doesn't have to stay that way.

360
00:27:11,498 --> 00:27:13,796
How come you know so much about it?

361
00:27:13,867 --> 00:27:15,995
Caspar isn't laying any more bets with you.

362
00:27:21,043 --> 00:27:23,910
You really must have Mink
jumping through hoops.

363
00:27:23,980 --> 00:27:27,314
Like I say, you can't have too many.

364
00:27:31,623 --> 00:27:35,617
- We got a deal?
- I'll think about it.

365
00:27:38,097 --> 00:27:40,430
I wouldn't want it any other way.

366
00:27:43,370 --> 00:27:45,931
Hey, Adolph.

367
00:27:47,875 --> 00:27:50,845
- My credit still good with you? - Mmm.

368
00:27:50,912 --> 00:27:53,608
Give me a hundred across
on Tailor Made in the third tonight.

369
00:27:53,682 --> 00:27:57,016
- Lazarre won't like it.
- Try 50 across.

370
00:27:57,086 --> 00:27:59,520
I'll try.
It's another 150 you'll owe him.

371
00:27:59,589 --> 00:28:03,048
- Only if I lose, Adolph.
- Tommy, the way you're goin'--

372
00:28:03,127 --> 00:28:06,689
- Hey, horses got knees?
- I don't know. Fetlocks.

373
00:28:06,765 --> 00:28:10,724
Well, if I was a horse, I'd be down on my
fetlocks praying you don't bet on me.

374
00:28:10,802 --> 00:28:13,169
- Drift, small guy.
- Drop dead, ape.

375
00:28:13,239 --> 00:28:15,537
Come on, Tom. Boss wants to see ya.

376
00:28:15,608 --> 00:28:18,009
He didn't have time to engrave nothin' formal.

377
00:28:38,200 --> 00:28:42,661
What you mean, he's eatin' too much?
What's the goddamn doctor know?

378
00:28:43,774 --> 00:28:46,538
- What you eat for lunch?
- A hot dog.

379
00:28:46,610 --> 00:28:50,274
-Just a hot dog?
- A hot dog and mustard.

380
00:28:50,348 --> 00:28:54,911
A hot dog and mustard.

381
00:28:59,926 --> 00:29:03,988
You hear that, Dane?
My kid is as smart as a whip.

382
00:29:04,064 --> 00:29:06,828
Even Uncle Eddie thinks that's funny.

383
00:29:06,901 --> 00:29:09,803
Okay.

384
00:29:10,972 --> 00:29:14,500
Go ahead. Which hand is the penny in?

385
00:29:15,778 --> 00:29:18,372
Choose again.

386
00:29:22,386 --> 00:29:25,584
Okay. Here you go.
 Take the penny. Shiny new penny.

387
00:29:31,330 --> 00:29:35,233
- I ain't got a penny, boss.
- That's a penny you owe him.

388
00:29:35,302 --> 00:29:38,829
Hello, Tom. What's the rumpus?
You like kids?

389
00:29:38,905 --> 00:29:42,171
- No.
- Have a seat. Go ahead.

390
00:29:43,678 --> 00:29:45,613
Well, you're missin' out on a complete life.

391
00:29:45,681 --> 00:29:48,172
I know, kids, big deal.

392
00:29:48,250 --> 00:29:51,186
Still, I'm telling you.

393
00:29:51,254 --> 00:29:54,815
Anyways, thanks for comin' by.

394
00:29:56,327 --> 00:29:58,921
I just wrote this check out
to your bookmaker Lazarre.

395
00:29:58,996 --> 00:30:01,795
It's for an even 1,500,
which is more than I hear you owe him,

396
00:30:01,867 --> 00:30:05,200
but I figured you could always use some money
 on the cuff, a high roller such as yourself.

397
00:30:05,270 --> 00:30:08,365
- What do you say?
- Thanks.

398
00:30:10,443 --> 00:30:12,810
Always the yapper, huh?

399
00:30:12,880 --> 00:30:17,250
Well, you're welcome. You wanna know
 why I'm puttin' you square with Lazarre?

400
00:30:17,318 --> 00:30:20,651
- Not particularly.
- I want everybody to be friends.

401
00:30:20,722 --> 00:30:23,089
I do this, you're friends with Lazarre,

402
00:30:23,158 --> 00:30:25,820
he's friends with you,
you're friends with me.

403
00:30:25,895 --> 00:30:30,333
All you gotta do to show you're a friend
 is give me Bernie Bernbaum.

404
00:30:30,400 --> 00:30:33,837
You know it's the right thing anyway.
The shmatte steals from me.

405
00:30:33,905 --> 00:30:37,933
I can't have Leo giving him a shiny new penny.

406
00:30:38,010 --> 00:30:40,171
So the deal is,
I give you Bernie,

407
00:30:40,245 --> 00:30:42,771
smooth it over with Leo
and you bail me out with Lazarre.

408
00:30:42,849 --> 00:30:44,976
Yeah. Then we're all friends again.

409
00:30:45,051 --> 00:30:47,782
You, me, Leo, the Dane.

410
00:30:51,559 --> 00:30:54,529
Friends is a mental state.

411
00:30:54,596 --> 00:30:58,294
- What do you say, kid?
- I'll think about it.

412
00:31:01,103 --> 00:31:04,096
You hear that, Dane?
The kid's a thinker. That's terrific.

413
00:31:04,174 --> 00:31:08,043
- Does he want a pillow for his head?
 - Okay, kid. Think about it.

414
00:31:08,112 --> 00:31:11,912
It's a mental state.
If it'll help you think,

415
00:31:11,983 --> 00:31:14,544
you should know
that if you don't do this thing,

416
00:31:14,620 --> 00:31:17,180
you're not gonna be in any shape
 to walk out of here.

417
00:31:18,992 --> 00:31:22,553
Would that be physically,
or just a mental state?

418
00:31:29,538 --> 00:31:32,905
That ain't friendly, kid.
I make you a nice offer,

419
00:31:32,975 --> 00:31:35,501
you give me the high hat.

420
00:32:15,526 --> 00:32:18,620
Hold it.

421
00:32:31,178 --> 00:32:34,409
Jesus, Tom.

422
00:33:15,030 --> 00:33:17,191
Just in the nick of time, huh?

423
00:33:21,104 --> 00:33:24,939
Well, no harm done.
Unless your friend broke his foot.

424
00:33:25,008 --> 00:33:28,376
- Where am I?
 - Where are you? Johnny Caspar's pleasure dome.

425
00:33:28,446 --> 00:33:31,381
Same as when you left us
 about ten seconds ago.

426
00:33:31,449 --> 00:33:33,816
Hello, Tom. How are ya?

427
00:33:33,886 --> 00:33:36,081
Care to scrape a knuckle
 on your playmate here?

428
00:33:36,155 --> 00:33:38,954
- No. Thanks though, Andy.
- Well, if you
change your mind,

429
00:33:39,025 --> 00:33:42,358
we'll be interrogating for a while.

430
00:33:42,429 --> 00:33:45,797
- What was that party about, anyway?
- We do this every weekend.

431
00:33:45,867 --> 00:33:48,461
Jesus, what is the matter with you people?

432
00:33:48,537 --> 00:33:51,335
Well, they said make it hurt,
so we make it hurt.

433
00:33:57,714 --> 00:33:59,649
Drink, O'Doole?

434
00:33:59,717 --> 00:34:01,947
I'm on duty.

435
00:34:02,019 --> 00:34:04,818
To Volstead.

436
00:34:06,258 --> 00:34:08,385
- Any news about Rug?

437
00:34:08,460 --> 00:34:10,952
Still dead, far as I know.

438
00:34:11,030 --> 00:34:13,760
- Get a slug out of him?
- Yeah, .22.

439
00:34:13,833 --> 00:34:16,564
Listen, Tom,
 I'm just the chief around here,

440
00:34:16,637 --> 00:34:18,696
so don't bother tellin' me
 if you don't happen to feel like it,

441
00:34:18,772 --> 00:34:20,707
but what the hell is Leo doin'?

442
00:34:20,775 --> 00:34:25,236
Make him listen to you, Tom.
It ain't right, all this fuss over one sheeny.

443
00:34:25,314 --> 00:34:28,249
Let Caspar have Bernie.
What's one Hebrew more or less?

444
00:34:28,317 --> 00:34:30,252
We're burnin' our meal ticket here.

445
00:34:30,320 --> 00:34:32,550
Leo will do what suits him,
and you'll do what he tells you.

446
00:34:32,622 --> 00:34:34,556
Last I heard, Leo was still running this town.

447
00:34:34,624 --> 00:34:37,253
Yeah, well, he won't be for long if this keeps up.

448
00:34:37,328 --> 00:34:40,092
It's no good for anyone.
You said as much yourself.

449
00:34:40,164 --> 00:34:44,363
First off, O'Doole, I can say what I please
to Leo and about him.

450
00:34:44,436 --> 00:34:46,428
You can't.

451
00:34:46,506 --> 00:34:50,101
Second, once Leo decides, that's that.

452
00:34:50,176 --> 00:34:52,611
If that sticks going down,
there are plenty of coppers I know...

453
00:34:52,680 --> 00:34:55,547
who wouldn't mind bein' chief and could swallow it clean.

454
00:34:55,616 --> 00:34:59,713
Jesus, Tom, I was just speculatin'
 about a hypothesis.

455
00:34:59,788 --> 00:35:01,848
I know I don't know nothin'.

456
00:35:01,924 --> 00:35:04,290
It's just a--
just a damn mess, is all.

457
00:35:28,589 --> 00:35:30,523
Hello, Officer.
I'd like to report an intruder...

458
00:35:30,591 --> 00:35:33,652
at 346 West Lewis--

459
00:35:33,728 --> 00:35:37,323
Who's this?
Hello, Shad. Tom Reagan here.

460
00:35:40,269 --> 00:35:43,068
- False alarm, huh?
 - Yeah. My mother. She didn't recognize me.

461
00:35:43,140 --> 00:35:45,472
Let me talk to Mulveany. Miss me?

462
00:35:45,542 --> 00:35:48,011
Drop dead.

463
00:35:48,079 --> 00:35:50,138
- Mulveany here.
- Sean?

464
00:35:50,214 --> 00:35:52,148
Tell O'Doole to get a car over
to Leo's tonight.

465
00:35:52,216 --> 00:35:55,186
If we're banging away at Caspar,
we oughta be ready for him to bang back.

466
00:35:57,590 --> 00:36:01,357
I was in the neighborhood, feeling a bit daffy,

467
00:36:01,428 --> 00:36:04,398
so I thought I'd drop in for an aperitif.

468
00:36:06,133 --> 00:36:09,069
- Rug Daniels is dead.
- Gee, that's tough.

469
00:36:09,137 --> 00:36:11,332
Don't get hysterical.

470
00:36:11,406 --> 00:36:15,002
I've had enough excitement for one night
without a dame going all weepy on me.

471
00:36:15,078 --> 00:36:17,205
- I barely knew the gentleman.
-Rug?

472
00:36:17,280 --> 00:36:21,650
A bit of a shakedown artist,
not above the occasional grift.

473
00:36:21,719 --> 00:36:25,520
Bet you'd understand that.
All in all, not a bad guy,

474
00:36:25,590 --> 00:36:28,991
if looks, brains and personality don't count.

475
00:36:29,060 --> 00:36:31,757
- You better hope they don't.
- Yeah, well--

476
00:36:31,831 --> 00:36:34,425
We're none of us the saint
I hear your brother is.

477
00:36:34,501 --> 00:36:36,696
- Who killed him?
- Leo thinks Caspar did.

478
00:36:36,770 --> 00:36:38,738
- But you know better.
- I do now.

479
00:36:38,805 --> 00:36:42,071
You see, Caspar just tried to buy me
 into fixing his tiff with Leo,

480
00:36:42,143 --> 00:36:44,908
which he'd hardly do if he was waging war.

481
00:36:44,980 --> 00:36:49,041
So I figure you killed him, angel.
You or St. Bernard.

482
00:36:49,118 --> 00:36:52,919
Why would I or my brother
 kill Rug Daniels or anybody else?

483
00:36:52,989 --> 00:36:57,051
Rug was following you.
He knew about you and me,

484
00:36:57,128 --> 00:36:59,756
and that wouldn't help
your play with Leo, would it?

485
00:36:59,830 --> 00:37:01,924
You think I murdered someone?

486
00:37:02,000 --> 00:37:05,094
Come on, Tom. You know me a little.

487
00:37:05,170 --> 00:37:07,696
Nobody knows anybody.
Not that well.

488
00:37:07,774 --> 00:37:09,969
You know, or you wouldn't be here.

489
00:37:10,043 --> 00:37:13,411
Not at all, sugar.
I came to hear your side of the story.

490
00:37:13,480 --> 00:37:18,111
How horrible Rug was, how he goaded you
 into it, how he tried to shake you down.

491
00:37:18,186 --> 00:37:20,279
- That's not why you came either.
- Tell me why I came.

492
00:37:20,355 --> 00:37:23,484
- The oldest reason there is.
- There are friendlier places to drink.

493
00:37:23,559 --> 00:37:25,493
- Why can't you admit it?
- Admit what?

494
00:37:25,561 --> 00:37:28,895
That you don't like me seeing Leo
 'cause you're jealous.

495
00:37:28,965 --> 00:37:31,263
Admit that you've got a heart,

496
00:37:31,334 --> 00:37:33,803
even though it may be small and feeble...

497
00:37:33,871 --> 00:37:36,066
and you can't remember
 the last time you used it.

498
00:37:36,140 --> 00:37:39,304
If I'd known we were gonna cast
 our feelings into words,

499
00:37:39,378 --> 00:37:42,007
I'd have memorized the Song of Solomon.

500
00:37:44,017 --> 00:37:47,249
Maybe that's why I like you, Tom.

501
00:37:47,321 --> 00:37:50,119
I never knew anybody
that made being a son of a bitch...

502
00:37:50,191 --> 00:37:52,888
such a point of pride.

503
00:37:52,961 --> 00:37:55,953
Though one day you'll pay the price for it.

504
00:37:57,299 --> 00:38:01,168
Okay, Verna.
But until then, let's get stinko.

505
00:38:01,237 --> 00:38:03,798
Let's do something else first.

506
00:42:08,599 --> 00:42:11,397
- Who's winning?
- We are, for the nonce.

507
00:42:11,468 --> 00:42:12,729
What's the disposition?

508
00:42:12,829 --> 00:42:15,729
Last night, four to one.
Dana Cudahy went up with the house.

509
00:42:15,866 --> 00:42:17,903
- And theirs?
- One burned.

510
00:42:17,977 --> 00:42:19,740
- The other three?
- Lead.

511
00:42:19,812 --> 00:42:21,837
- Whose?
- Leo's.

512
00:42:21,915 --> 00:42:24,179
The old man's still an artist with a Thompson.

513
00:42:24,251 --> 00:42:26,219
Yeah, do that.

514
00:42:31,692 --> 00:42:34,594
Son of a bitch. No chief.

515
00:42:34,663 --> 00:42:38,031
- Who's mindin' the goddamn store?
-Can't raise O'Doole?

516
00:42:38,101 --> 00:42:40,203
No, nor the mayor either.

517
00:42:44,741 --> 00:42:47,437
I don't know, Leo.
 I warned you not to hit Caspar's club.

518
00:42:47,511 --> 00:42:50,310
- I'm still here, ain't I?
-Caspar's play hurt you anyway.

519
00:42:50,381 --> 00:42:52,872
That sorry son of a bitch
 just slit his own throat.

520
00:42:52,951 --> 00:42:56,080
Listen to me, Leo.
Last night made you look vulnerable.

521
00:42:56,155 --> 00:42:59,592
You don't hold elected office in this town.
 You run it because people think you run it.

522
00:42:59,659 --> 00:43:02,423
Once they stop thinking it,
you stop running it.

523
00:43:06,000 --> 00:43:09,061
I mean it, Leo.
Start taking Caspar seriously.

524
00:43:09,137 --> 00:43:13,369
I know, I know. Retreat to win, give up
Bernie. That'll solve all our problems.

525
00:43:13,442 --> 00:43:15,502
Won't anymore, I'll grant you that.

526
00:43:15,578 --> 00:43:18,046
But going toe-to-toe with a psychopath
 will get you nowhere.

527
00:43:18,114 --> 00:43:20,811
It'll force people to choose sides
just when you're looking shaky.

528
00:43:24,256 --> 00:43:26,486
Why aren't there any police here?

529
00:43:26,558 --> 00:43:28,583
Why weren't there any police
at your place last night?

530
00:43:28,660 --> 00:43:31,255
- I didn't ask for any.
- I did.

531
00:43:34,400 --> 00:43:37,199
Mother hen, huh?
What's the matter, Tommy?

532
00:43:37,271 --> 00:43:40,799
- Don't you think I can take care of myself?
 - I know you can't.

533
00:43:40,875 --> 00:43:43,742
Here's the smart play, Leo.
You lay back, you give Bernie up,

534
00:43:43,811 --> 00:43:45,803
you let Caspar think he's made his point.

535
00:43:45,881 --> 00:43:48,873
- Then you wait for him to show a weakness.
- Please, Tom.

536
00:43:48,951 --> 00:43:51,182
You're sticking on Bernie.
You're sticking your neck out...

537
00:43:51,254 --> 00:43:54,189
for a guy who'd chop you off at the heels
 if there was two bits in it.

538
00:43:56,694 --> 00:43:59,390
Tom,

539
00:43:59,463 --> 00:44:02,797
things aren't as, uh, clear-cut as you make it.

540
00:44:04,403 --> 00:44:08,602
Bernie's--
 Well, hell,you know about me and Verna.

541
00:44:08,675 --> 00:44:12,544
Things now are, uh--

542
00:44:12,613 --> 00:44:16,380
Not that I haven't been a gentleman, but--

543
00:44:18,453 --> 00:44:21,912
I plan to ask her to marry me, Tom.

544
00:44:26,630 --> 00:44:29,997
I guess you think that's a bonehead play.

545
00:44:34,305 --> 00:44:38,106
- You think she wants you to?
- How the hell do I know?

546
00:44:38,177 --> 00:44:40,873
I think she does.
Yeah, of course she does.

547
00:44:40,946 --> 00:44:44,815
I know you think different,
but, well, we just, uh--

548
00:44:44,884 --> 00:44:47,251
We just differ on that.

549
00:44:50,057 --> 00:44:53,221
Leo, Caspar didn't kill Rug.

550
00:44:53,295 --> 00:44:57,061
- Course he did.
- No. Think about it just this one time.

551
00:44:57,132 --> 00:44:59,158
- Who was Rug following?
- Huh?

552
00:44:59,235 --> 00:45:02,797
It needn't have been that sinister.
Strange man follows her down a dark alleyway.

553
00:45:02,873 --> 00:45:05,273
- I told you she can look after herself.
 - Verna wouldn't panic,

554
00:45:05,342 --> 00:45:08,540
shoot someone just because
he was following her.

555
00:45:08,613 --> 00:45:12,413
Nah, it wouldn't have happened like that,
and if it had she would have told me.

556
00:45:12,484 --> 00:45:15,716
They pulled a .22 slug out of him.
A pop gun, Leo, a woman's gun.

557
00:45:15,788 --> 00:45:17,983
I know you don't like her, Tom,

558
00:45:18,057 --> 00:45:21,050
but I trust Verna as much as I trust you.

559
00:45:22,629 --> 00:45:24,564
Okay, Leo.

560
00:45:24,632 --> 00:45:26,930
Maybe it wasn't that innocent.

561
00:45:27,001 --> 00:45:30,665
Maybe Rug knew something she didn't like him
 knowing and wouldn't want you to know.

562
00:45:30,739 --> 00:45:34,403
Rug was following her.
Maybe he knew where she was sleeping,

563
00:45:34,477 --> 00:45:36,411
and who with.

564
00:45:40,484 --> 00:45:42,975
Maybes don't make it so.

565
00:45:44,054 --> 00:45:46,046
There's more than maybes.

566
00:45:46,124 --> 00:45:49,686
You've trusted me before, you've never
 lost anything by it. Trust me on this.

567
00:45:52,498 --> 00:45:55,957
- This is too important. - I don't ask much, and I don't ask often.

568
00:45:56,036 --> 00:45:58,504
Trust me on this.

569
00:45:58,572 --> 00:46:01,838
- Tommy.
- Trust me on this, or to hell with you.

570
00:46:04,479 --> 00:46:06,846
You don't mean that.

571
00:46:09,618 --> 00:46:11,553
She was with me...

572
00:46:11,621 --> 00:46:15,022
the night Rug
was following her,

573
00:46:15,091 --> 00:46:17,060
the night you dropped by.

574
00:46:30,743 --> 00:46:33,076
Oh.

575
00:48:29,218 --> 00:48:31,983
Okay, Leo. Okay.
I'll throw him out.

576
00:48:34,124 --> 00:48:36,685
Yeah, do that.

577
00:48:37,762 --> 00:48:39,957
It's the kiss-off.

578
00:48:40,031 --> 00:48:43,365
If I never see him again,
it'll be soon enough.

579
00:48:53,714 --> 00:48:55,739
- Hello?
- Hello, Frankie.

580
00:48:55,816 --> 00:48:58,251
It's Tom.
How's the flunky business?

581
00:48:59,554 --> 00:49:01,819
I've had worse.
Your ventilator mending?

582
00:49:05,128 --> 00:49:07,563
- I'd like to see him.

583
00:49:09,199 --> 00:49:11,429
Ah. All right, let me know.

584
00:49:56,756 --> 00:50:00,716
It worked, whatever you did.

585
00:50:00,794 --> 00:50:04,231
Leo says we're quits.

586
00:50:04,298 --> 00:50:06,960
But you know I didn't have anything
to do with Rug.

587
00:50:07,034 --> 00:50:09,765
Maybe not.

588
00:50:09,838 --> 00:50:11,806
Anyway, that isn't what soured him on you.

589
00:50:11,874 --> 00:50:14,207
Oh, you and me, huh?

590
00:50:15,979 --> 00:50:19,609
You always take the long way around
to get what you want, don't you, Tom?

591
00:50:21,685 --> 00:50:24,120
You could have just asked.

592
00:50:27,025 --> 00:50:29,927
What did I want?

593
00:50:29,996 --> 00:50:32,624
Me.

594
00:50:58,663 --> 00:51:01,394
Yeah?

595
00:51:01,467 --> 00:51:03,401
Yeah, yeah.

596
00:51:03,469 --> 00:51:05,802
When?

597
00:51:05,872 --> 00:51:07,806
Okay.

598
00:51:12,646 --> 00:51:15,410
You still up?

599
00:51:15,483 --> 00:51:17,714
Yeah.

600
00:51:21,524 --> 00:51:24,618
What are you chewin' over?

601
00:51:24,694 --> 00:51:26,925
Dream I had once.

602
00:51:28,832 --> 00:51:31,802
I was walking in the woods.
I don't know why.

603
00:51:33,371 --> 00:51:36,499
Wind came whippin'.
Blew me hat off.

604
00:51:38,477 --> 00:51:41,412
And you chased it, right?

605
00:51:41,480 --> 00:51:43,881
You ran and ran.

606
00:51:43,950 --> 00:51:47,114
You finally caught up to it.

607
00:51:47,188 --> 00:51:51,284
And you picked it up,
but it wasn't a hat anymore.

608
00:51:51,359 --> 00:51:55,319
It had changed into something else,
something wonderful.

609
00:51:55,397 --> 00:51:58,231
No, it stayed a hat.

610
00:51:58,301 --> 00:52:00,792
And no, I didn't chase it.

611
00:52:02,138 --> 00:52:05,973
Nothing more foolish
than a man chasin' his hat.

612
00:52:06,043 --> 00:52:08,274
Where are you going?

613
00:52:08,346 --> 00:52:11,110
Just have to do a few things.

614
00:52:11,182 --> 00:52:13,253
You and Leo might still be able
to patch things up.

615
00:52:13,442 --> 00:52:14,740
Me and Leo are finished.

616
00:52:14,775 --> 00:52:17,470
-Nothing's gonna change that.
- You never know.

617
00:52:18,108 --> 00:52:19,258
He's got a big heart.

618
00:52:19,308 --> 00:52:21,788
 We're quits as far as I'm concerned,
 never mind him.

619
00:52:22,162 --> 00:52:26,429
And if Leo did want me back,
he's an even bigger sap than I thought.

620
00:52:26,501 --> 00:52:28,993
Then why don't we just
pick up and leave town?

621
00:52:29,071 --> 00:52:31,938
There's nothing keeping you here.

622
00:52:32,007 --> 00:52:33,942
I know there's nothing keeping me.

623
00:52:34,010 --> 00:52:37,343
- What about Bernie?
- He could go with us.

624
00:52:38,582 --> 00:52:40,744
You, me and Bernie?
Where would we go, Verna?

625
00:52:40,818 --> 00:52:42,752
Niagara Falls?

626
00:52:42,820 --> 00:52:44,755
Why do you hate him?

627
00:52:44,823 --> 00:52:46,757
- I don't hate anyone.
-Or like anyone.

628
00:52:51,831 --> 00:52:54,026
Where is Bernie?

629
00:52:54,100 --> 00:52:56,592
- Why?
- Leo can't protect him anymore.

630
00:52:56,670 --> 00:53:00,129
I oughta tell him to skip.

631
00:53:00,208 --> 00:53:02,142
The Royale, room 302.

632
00:53:07,416 --> 00:53:11,046
I guess we both double-crossed Leo, huh?

633
00:53:11,121 --> 00:53:13,055
There's no gettin' around that.

634
00:53:14,191 --> 00:53:16,990
I guess he's well rid of both of us.

635
00:53:17,061 --> 00:53:21,465
The two of us, we're about
bad enough to deserve each other.

636
00:53:24,937 --> 00:53:26,872
Are we?

637
00:53:28,975 --> 00:53:31,877
We're a couple of heels, Tom.

638
00:53:31,946 --> 00:53:34,642
Yes, we are.

639
00:53:39,287 --> 00:53:43,019
Hello, Tom.

640
00:53:43,092 --> 00:53:46,324
Uh, you know O'Doole and the mayor.

641
00:53:46,397 --> 00:53:49,696
- Hello, boys.
- Tom's a big booster. Always has been.

642
00:53:49,767 --> 00:53:53,864
That's fine, that's fine.
Well, Tom and I got the proverbial fat to chew.

643
00:53:53,938 --> 00:53:56,737
-Just let us know if you need anything.
- Yeah. Happy days.

644
00:53:56,809 --> 00:53:59,869
Have a seat, kid.
Yeah, that's it.

645
00:53:59,945 --> 00:54:03,279
So,you had enough time to think about things?

646
00:54:03,350 --> 00:54:07,447
- Yeah, well, uh, circumstances have changed.
- Don't I know it.

647
00:54:07,522 --> 00:54:10,616
Last night I know the Dane
was disappointed the bulls showed up...

648
00:54:10,692 --> 00:54:13,355
before Frankie and Tic-Tac
really pinned your ears back,

649
00:54:13,429 --> 00:54:17,890
but I said, ''Relax, Eddie.
 I got a feeling about this kid.

650
00:54:17,967 --> 00:54:22,199
The kid and Leo are gonna go bust-o.
 Matter of time.''

651
00:54:22,272 --> 00:54:24,969
I said, ''The kid is too smart for Leo.''
 That's what I said.

652
00:54:25,042 --> 00:54:28,103
Like a psychic. Ask the Dane if I did.
 Like a goddamn psychic.

653
00:54:28,180 --> 00:54:30,671
-Go ahead, ask him.
- You vouch for that psychic business?

654
00:54:30,749 --> 00:54:33,310
- That's right, smart guy.
-I know you knew...

655
00:54:33,386 --> 00:54:36,412
protecting the shmatte was a dumb idea.

656
00:54:36,489 --> 00:54:40,187
I know you've been wise
to all of Leo's dumb ideas lately.

657
00:54:40,260 --> 00:54:42,387
Only a matter of time-- bust-o.

658
00:54:42,463 --> 00:54:45,627
That's why last night
we didn't put the arm on you, only Leo.

659
00:54:45,700 --> 00:54:48,884
Seeing how you squiffed your play on Leo,
 I can only be so grateful.

660
00:54:48,984 --> 00:54:52,195
Oh, that's real brave
coming from Little Miss Punching Bag.

661
00:54:52,295 --> 00:54:53,564
Okay, Eddie.

662
00:54:53,642 --> 00:54:56,908
- Friends now, huh?
- Nuts.

663
00:54:58,582 --> 00:55:00,517
So, I guess you'll be looking for a job, eh, kid?

664
00:55:00,585 --> 00:55:03,247
I might be.

665
00:55:03,321 --> 00:55:05,347
You got references?
You been to college?

666
00:55:05,424 --> 00:55:09,019
We only take yeggs what's been to college.
 Ain't that right, Dane?

667
00:55:11,898 --> 00:55:15,164
I'm joking, of course.
We all know you could be useful to us,

668
00:55:15,236 --> 00:55:17,170
a smart kid such as yourself.

669
00:55:17,238 --> 00:55:21,039
The man who walks behind the man,
who whispers in his ear.

670
00:55:21,109 --> 00:55:24,772
- I guess you could be useful in spades.
- Yeah, I can do plenty for you.

671
00:55:24,847 --> 00:55:29,284
- Can you get Leo off me?
 - I'm tellin' you not to worry about Leo.

672
00:55:29,352 --> 00:55:31,287
- We got plans for him.
- Oh,yeah?

673
00:55:31,355 --> 00:55:34,188
- Like what?
- Not so fast there, ''kaputnik.''

674
00:55:34,258 --> 00:55:36,784
I-I think what the Dane is trying to say is,

675
00:55:36,861 --> 00:55:38,795
there'll be time to talk about that.

676
00:55:38,863 --> 00:55:41,230
We can table that for a later date.

677
00:55:42,701 --> 00:55:47,298
See, last time we jawed,
you gave me the high hat.

678
00:55:47,374 --> 00:55:49,899
I guess I'm sayin'...

679
00:55:49,976 --> 00:55:53,504
you gotta put something on the table first.

680
00:55:53,581 --> 00:55:56,312
- Ante up.
- Fair enough. Where do we start?

681
00:55:56,385 --> 00:55:59,912
Hear that, Dane? All business.
I told you he was a good kid.

682
00:55:59,988 --> 00:56:02,184
''Where do we start?''
All business.

683
00:56:02,258 --> 00:56:05,352
Well, we can start, for instance,
with the shmatte.

684
00:56:05,428 --> 00:56:07,397
Like, where's the shmatte?
You could maybe tell us that.

685
00:56:07,464 --> 00:56:11,595
The Royale, room 302.
And you might find Mink with him.

686
00:56:11,670 --> 00:56:13,638
The hell you say.

687
00:56:13,705 --> 00:56:15,832
Sure. Bernie and Mink are cozy as lice.

688
00:56:15,907 --> 00:56:19,207
- And it ain't just business.
- This guy is lying.

689
00:56:19,278 --> 00:56:21,212
- Why would I?
- This guy is wrong.

690
00:56:21,280 --> 00:56:26,386
This guy is all wrong.
Mink is clean and this clown is a smart guy.

691
